body:
I know this is an extremely basic question, but I have a slight misunderstanding (?) regarding this question: How many possible outcomes are there when flipping two coins? At first glance, this is a really easy problem: 2 x 2 = 4 ! But if I list all the possible outcomes: {H, H}
{H, T}
{T, H}
{T, T} I noticed that there are really three "distinct" outcomes: {H, H}
{H, T}
{T, T} Is it wrong to consider {H, T} and {T, H} the same? Why or why not?
